<subSubSection id="1DDA657FFFF6D907FF7CD256FA3BA371" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="535" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" type="key">
<keyStep id="EE342E51FFF6D904FF7CD256FA3CA4D9" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD256FA3BA412" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD256FA3BA412" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
1. Elytra uniformly dark brown with pattern of white setae consisting of a median wavy transverse stripe, two basal patches, and an apical band (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FE93D23BFE68A412" box="[376,463,1607,1628]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1884,1906]" captionTargetBox="[348,1266,201,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[306,1288,195,1870]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Elonus species in dorsal view. a, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin. b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin. c, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♀, from Wisconsin. d, Elonus simplex Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype). e, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♀, from Mississippi. g, Elonus excavatus Werner, ♂, from Arizona (holotype). h, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype). d, Elonus nebulosus (LeConte), ♂, from Texas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037058/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
Figure 
<date id="217E1034FFF6D904FE55D23BFE68A412" box="[446,463,1607,1628]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">1i</date>
</figureCitation>
)........................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="92C04D77FFF6D904FB97D234FA3BA412" authority="(LeConte, 1875)" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1875" baseAuthorityName="LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[1148,1436,1607,1629]" class="Insecta" family="Aderidae" genus="Elonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nebulosus">
<emphasis id="67B4EAE6FFF6D904FB97D234FB51A413" box="[1148,1270,1607,1629]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">E. nebulosus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="31514B05FFF6D904FAE8D23BFA33A412" author="LeConte" box="[1283,1428,1607,1628]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" refString="LeConte, J. L. (1875) Descriptions of new Coleoptera of the United States with notes on geographical distribution. Transactions of the American Entomoloigcal Society, 5, 169 - 176." type="journal article" year="1875">LeConte, 1875</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD219FA3CA4D9" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD219FA3CA4D9" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
- Elytra bicolored: base entirely orange or with an orange blotch on each elytron, rest of the elytra brown to black (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FAF5D219FA33A434" box="[1310,1428,1637,1658]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1884,1906]" captionTargetBox="[348,1266,201,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[306,1288,195,1870]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Elonus species in dorsal view. a, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin. b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin. c, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♀, from Wisconsin. d, Elonus simplex Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype). e, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♀, from Mississippi. g, Elonus excavatus Werner, ♂, from Arizona (holotype). h, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype). d, Elonus nebulosus (LeConte), ♂, from Texas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037058/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 1a–h</figureCitation>
).................................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="EE342E51FFF6D904FF7CD2E3FA3CA4A1" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD2E3FA3BA4FA" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" box="[151,1436,1695,1716]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD2E3FA3BA4FA" box="[151,1436,1695,1716]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
2. Short elytral pubescence between punctures dense, white, uniform, distinctly visible under lateral illumination (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FAE6D2E3FAD9A4FA" box="[1293,1406,1695,1716]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1832,1854]" captionTargetBox="[237,1368,210,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[218,1378,193,1820]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Elytral pigmentation and pubescence of Elonus species. a – d, basal orange pattern variation. a, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ from Texas; c, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; d, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. e – j, elytral pubescence. e, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype); f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi; g, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype); h, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; i, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype) (note the lateral patches of short white recumbent hairs (white arrows); j, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037064/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 4e–f</figureCitation>
) 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD2C1FA3CA4A1" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD2C1FA3CA4A1" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
- Short elytral pubescence between punctures sparser, darker, hardly visible, or limited to suture and a post-median stripe (Figure 
<quantity id="92389B11FFF6D904FEEED2A6FEB9A4A1" box="[261,286,1754,1775]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="4.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" unit="g" value="4.0">4g</quantity>
–j)............................................................................................ 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="EE342E51FFF6D904FF7CD28BFA3BA52A" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD28BFA3BA564" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD28BFA3BA564" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
3. Elytra brown (except base), uniformly covered with long erected yellow setae (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FC31D28BFB9FA542" box="[986,1080,1783,1804]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1832,1854]" captionTargetBox="[237,1368,210,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[218,1378,193,1820]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Elytral pigmentation and pubescence of Elonus species. a – d, basal orange pattern variation. a, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ from Texas; c, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; d, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. e – j, elytral pubescence. e, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype); f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi; g, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype); h, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; i, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype) (note the lateral patches of short white recumbent hairs (white arrows); j, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037064/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 4f</figureCitation>
). forelegs and midlegs reddish. Male mesotibiae strongly curved (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FE1AD369FDEDA564" box="[497,586,1813,1834]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1665,1687]" captionTargetBox="[272,1340,337,1620]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[225,1362,313,1633]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abdominal sternites and leg morphology of male Elonus species. Abdominal sternites in ventral view (a – g) (note the variable anterior extension of the golden pubescence (white arrows )), tibiae of mesothoracic legs in dorsal view (h – n) and femora of metathoracic legs in ventral view (o – u) (note the presence of a proximal excavation in some species (empty arrowheads )). a, h, o, Elonus nebulosus (LeConte), from Texas; b, i, p, Elonus basalis (LeConte), from Wisconsin; c, j, q, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; d, k, r, Elonus hesperus Werner, from Mississippi; e, l, s, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype); f, t, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (holotype); m, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype): note the kink in the mesotibiae (black arrowhead); g, n, u, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037062/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 3l</figureCitation>
)................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="92C04D77FFF6D904FB4FD369FA3BA564" authority="Werner, 1990" authorityName="Werner" authorityYear="1990" box="[1188,1436,1812,1834]" class="Insecta" family="Aderidae" genus="Elonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperus">
<emphasis id="67B4EAE6FFF6D904FB4FD369FAB3A564" box="[1188,1300,1812,1834]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">E. hesperus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="31514B05FFF6D904FAF0D369FA3BA564" author="Werner" box="[1307,1436,1813,1834]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" refString="Werner, F. G. (1990) Revision of the Aderidae of eastern North America. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 98, 187 - 232." type="journal article" year="1990">Werner, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD34EFA3BA52A" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD34EFA3BA52A" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
- Elytra black, long pale pubescence darker, only with white setae along suture (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FC3BD34EFB97A509" box="[976,1072,1842,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1832,1854]" captionTargetBox="[237,1368,210,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[218,1378,193,1820]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Elytral pigmentation and pubescence of Elonus species. a – d, basal orange pattern variation. a, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ from Texas; c, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; d, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. e – j, elytral pubescence. e, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype); f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi; g, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype); h, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; i, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype) (note the lateral patches of short white recumbent hairs (white arrows); j, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037064/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 4e</figureCitation>
). Male mesotibiae with moderate curvature (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FEC2D333FE20A52A" box="[297,391,1871,1892]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1665,1687]" captionTargetBox="[272,1340,337,1620]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[225,1362,313,1633]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abdominal sternites and leg morphology of male Elonus species. Abdominal sternites in ventral view (a – g) (note the variable anterior extension of the golden pubescence (white arrows )), tibiae of mesothoracic legs in dorsal view (h – n) and femora of metathoracic legs in ventral view (o – u) (note the presence of a proximal excavation in some species (empty arrowheads )). a, h, o, Elonus nebulosus (LeConte), from Texas; b, i, p, Elonus basalis (LeConte), from Wisconsin; c, j, q, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; d, k, r, Elonus hesperus Werner, from Mississippi; e, l, s, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype); f, t, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (holotype); m, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype): note the kink in the mesotibiae (black arrowhead); g, n, u, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037062/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 3n</figureCitation>
)............................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="92C04D77FFF6D904FB65D32CFA3BA52A" authority="Werner, 1992" authorityName="Werner" authorityYear="1992" box="[1166,1436,1871,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Aderidae" genus="Elonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chisosensis">
<emphasis id="67B4EAE6FFF6D904FB65D32CFAB2A52B" box="[1166,1301,1871,1893]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">E. chisosensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="31514B05FFF6D904FAF0D333FA3BA52A" author="Werner" box="[1307,1436,1871,1892]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534" refString="Werner, F. G. (1992) The Nearctic species of Elonus (Coleoptera: Aderidae). Psyche, 99, 245 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 1992 / 97483" type="journal article" year="1992">Werner, 1992</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="EE342E51FFF6D904FF7CD311FA3BA594" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD311FA3CA5D1" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD311FA3CA5D1" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
4. Base of elytra marked with a solid, uninterrupted transverse orange stripe, only moderately narrower in scutellar region (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FAB0D311FF5EA5D1" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1832,1854]" captionTargetBox="[237,1368,210,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[218,1378,193,1820]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Elytral pigmentation and pubescence of Elonus species. a – d, basal orange pattern variation. a, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ from Texas; c, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; d, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. e – j, elytral pubescence. e, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype); f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi; g, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype); h, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; i, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype) (note the lateral patches of short white recumbent hairs (white arrows); j, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037064/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 4c</figureCitation>
)................................................................................................. 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="557F36F4FFF6D904FF7CD3DBFA3BA594" blockId="1.[151,1436,1578,2010]" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
<keyLead id="EE3195C1FFF6D904FF7CD3DBFA3BA594" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">
- Base of elytra marked with orange patches confined to humeral callus on each side; or orange markings forming a continuous stripe but with a strong constriction in the scutellar region (
<figureCitation id="CDFB2A71FFF6D904FCF3D3B9FC2AA594" box="[792,909,1989,2010]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1832,1854]" captionTargetBox="[237,1368,210,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[218,1378,193,1820]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Elytral pigmentation and pubescence of Elonus species. a – d, basal orange pattern variation. a, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin; b, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ from Texas; c, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; d, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi. e – j, elytral pubescence. e, Elonus chisosensis Werner, ♂, from Arizona (paratype); f, Elonus hesperus Werner, ♂, from Mississippi; g, Elonus excavatus Werner, from Arizona (paratype); h, Elonus basalis (LeConte), ♂, from Wisconsin; i, Elonus simplex Werner, from Arizona (paratype) (note the lateral patches of short white recumbent hairs (white arrows); j, Elonus gruberi n. sp., ♂ holotype, from Wisconsin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1037064/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="534">Figure 4a, b</figureCitation>
).............................. 
